<HEADLINE>
Hurricanes Fausto off Mexico, Bertha off New England pose no
threat to land
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY 2008-07-19 21:56:48 UTC
</P>
<P>
Hurricane Fausto strengthened Saturday far off Mexico's Pacific
coast, while Hurricane Bertha hovered over the Atlantic hundreds
of miles (kilometers) off the coast of New England.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. National Hurricane Center in Miami said neither storm is
expected to threaten land.
</P>
<P>
Tropical Storm Cristobal meanwhile formed off the southeastern
United States, sending bands of rain into Georgia and the
Carolinas. It is the first storm to threaten the U.S. this
hurricane season, the center said.
</P>
<P>
In the Pacific, Hurricane Fausto had maximum sustained winds of
85 mph (140 kph). It was centered was about 460 miles (735
kilometers) southwest of Manzanillo, Mexico, and was moving
northwest at 8 mph (13 kph).
</P>
<P>
Bertha remained a Category 1 hurricane and raced through the
Atlantic with winds near 75 mph (120 kph). It was located about
490 miles (790 kilometers) south of Cape Race, Newfoundland, and
was moving northeast at 25 mph (41kph).
</P>
<P>
Bertha battered Bermuda earlier this week, knocking out
electricity to thousands at the Atlantic tourist destination.
Bertha is the longest-lived July tropical storm in history, but
was expected to weaken in coming days, the hurricane center said.
</P>
